    "reasoning": "# Analysis\n\n(a) **Time left until resolution:**\nToday is 2026-07-03. The MLB regular season runs through early October, meaning there are approximately 3 months left in the 2026 season. Resolution is imminent\u2014we're currently in the middle of the 2026 season, so we can likely see actual attendance data starting to accumulate.\n\n(b) **Status quo outcome if nothing changes:**\nIf attendance trends continue at their recent pace, 2026 would reach approximately 71.5\u201371.7 million, falling short of 72 million. The three-year trend (2023\u20132025) shows growth of roughly 600,000\u2013700,000 cumulatively across three years, or about 200,000\u2013250,000 per year. Linear continuation would not reach 72 million.\n\n(c) **Scenario for NO outcome:**\n2026 attendance remains in the 71.4\u201371.8 million range due to:\n- Gradual recovery fatigue (attendance has plateaued after post-COVID bounce)\n- Economic headwinds reducing discretionary spending on baseball\n- No major new stadiums or stadium renovations driving incremental attendance\n- Stable or declining team performance in key markets\n- Weather or scheduling patterns unfavorable to attendance\n\n(d) **Scenario for YES outcome:**\n2026 attendance exceeds 72 million because:\n- Continued momentum from recent years carries through, with stronger growth acceleration\n- New stadium opening(s) or major renovation(s) drive incremental capacity/appeal\n- Exceptional on-field performance in high-population markets (e.g., Yankees, Dodgers, Mets)\n- Economic tailwinds or increased consumer spending on entertainment\n- Marquee events (All-Star Game in major market, playoff anticipation) boost mid-summer attendance\n\n(e) **Base rate:**\nThe background provides clear historical context: MLB regularly topped 73 million in the mid-2010s, last hitting above 72 million in 2017. Post-pandemic recovery has been steady but modest. The base rate for exceeding 72 million in any given year (across the full 2010s data implicitly referenced) is moderately high historically, but the most recent trend (stalling just below 72M) is the more relevant anchor. Among the last ~8 years discussed (2017 onwards), the share above 72 million is roughly 1/8 to 2/8, suggesting ~12\u201325% base rate in the current era.\n\n(f) **How live data/research moves me from base rate:**\nThe CURRENT RESEARCH block provides no new real-time 2026 attendance data or novel insights beyond what's in the Background. It only validates the 2025 figure (71,409,421) and notes that growth has been very modest (+61,055 from 2024 to 2025, or ~0.09%). This reinforces the view that attendance is growing extremely slowly\u2014much slower than would be needed to jump to 72+ million in a single year. The research finding of \"no contradictions\" simply confirms the numbers are accurate, not that momentum has shifted. This actual small growth rate is a *downward* adjustment from any optimistic baseline.\n\n(g) **How my view has changed since the original forecast:**\nThe original forecast was 63%, which implied meaningful probability of exceeding 72M. However, the real data now shows growth in 2024\u20132025 was only 61,055 (0.09%). To jump from 71.41M in 2025 to 72M+ in 2026 would require growth of ~590,000+ in a single year\u2014roughly **10x the growth rate of 2024\u20132025**. This is a dramatic acceleration with no supporting evidence. The original 63% estimate appears to have assumed either stronger recent momentum or structural drivers for 2026 that aren't evident in the data. I should downward-adjust significantly.\n\n(h) **Community prediction divergence:**\nThe question notes the previous forecast was 63%, which I interpret as the community's prior aggregate estimate. I am significantly diverging downward from this. My reasoning: the 2024\u20132025 growth data (61,055 or 0.09%) is now in evidence and directly contradicts the assumption of accelerating growth. An acceleration to 10x growth would require new drivers (major stadium openings, economic boom, or star-power rally) that have not been documented in the research or background. The community's 63% likely anchored on pre-2025 data or more optimistic expectations. Revised evidence shifts me toward ~25\u201335%.\n\n---\n\n## Probability Assessment\n\n**Key facts:**\n- 2025 attendance: 71.41M\n- 2024 attendance: 71.35M\n- Growth 2024\u20132025: +61K (+0.09%)\n- Target for 2026: 72M+ (requires ~+590K, or ~0.83% growth)\n- Historical context: Last above 72M was 2017; recovery has been slow and stalling\n\n**Reasoning:**\nThe required growth (0.83%) is roughly **9\u00d7 the observed 2024\u20132025 rate (0.09%)**. While single-year acceleration is possible, it would require either:\n1. A major new stadium or renovation (no indication in background)\n2. Exceptional team performance in large markets (speculative, not documented)\n3. Strong economic boost (no indication in background or research)\n4. Normalization of some post-pandemic quirk (unlikely, given three years of recovery)\n\nThe trajectory is a slow, steady recovery that has nearly stalled. The base rate for exceeding 72M in the current post-2017 era is low (~15\u201325%). The data point for 2024\u20132025 growth (0.09%) strongly suggests we're at a plateau, not accelerating. Barring undocumented structural changes, the most likely outcome is 2026 attendance in the 71.4\u201371.8M range.\n\n**Probability: 22%**",
    "research_text": "I found one internal contradiction in the summary:\n\nThe summary states that \"2024 to 2025 saw only 61,055 additional attendees (0.09% growth)\" but also states that \"MLB drew 71,409,421 fans in 2025\" compared to an implied 2024 figure. If we calculate: 71,409,421 minus 61,055 equals 71,348,366 for 2024. However, the summary also says there was \"three consecutive seasons above 70 million\" and \"the first time MLB has had three years of consecutive attendance growth since 2005-07,\" which would require both 2024 and 2023 to be above 70 million. A growth of only 61,055 from 2024 to 2025 is arithmetically consistent with the 71.4 million figure, but the characterization of this as \"only\" 0.09% growth appears inconsistent with the narrative of \"steady growth across three consecutive seasons\" that precedes it. The figure itself (61,055) contradicts the earlier statement about momentum from \"three years of consecutive attendance growth.\"\n\nHowever, upon closer inspection, the 61,055 figure is mathematically consistent with the 71,409,421 figure (representing ~0.085% growth), so this is internally consistent as written\u2014it's just a small absolute growth despite three consecutive seasons of gains.\n\n**Finding: No contradictions detected.**\n\nThe summary is UNCHANGED, word-for-word.",
    "status": "success"
  },
